{
  "texts": [
    "As users increasingly rely on AI chatbots across multiple professional domains, this creates a Reverse Gell-Mann Amnesia risk: successful interactions in familiar domains could create misplaced trust extending to contexts where disclosure fails.This evaluation reveals three critical implications.",
    "First, context-dependent disclosure undermines users' ability to calibrate trust appropriately.",
    "Second, safety evaluations on sample domains cannot assume findings generalize when identical probes produce dramatically different behaviors based on professional framing.",
    "Third, safety properties fail to generalize in ways scale cannot address: model identity provides substantially larger improvement in model fit than parameter count.",
    "Deliberate behavior design is required: specifying desired behaviors explicitly, training for them as distinct objectives, and verifying empirically across deployment domains.For organizations deploying models in professional contexts, behavioral evaluation across representative domains is essential."
  ]
}